    "segments": [
      {
        "start": 0.0,
        "duration": 2.9,
        "text": "Are these objects equal?"
      },
      {
        "start": 2.9,
        "duration": 4.7,
        "text": "By default, Python compares objects based on identity."
      },
      {
        "start": 7.6,
        "duration": 5.2,
        "text": "That means two objects are equal, only if they're literally the same object."
      },
      {
        "start": 12.8,
        "duration": 4.7,
        "text": "So this card object is only ever equal to itself."
      },
      {
        "start": 17.5,
        "duration": 5.3,
        "text": "It has to be the exact same object in memory."
      },
      {
        "start": 22.8,
        "duration": 4.8,
        "text": "Now, the question is, is it even useful to compare objects this way?"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.6,
        "duration": 4.1,
        "text": "Well, my useful answer is that it depends."
      },
      {
        "start": 31.7,
        "duration": 2.0,
        "text": "Let's rewind for a second."
      },
      {
        "start": 33.7,
        "duration": 3.3,
        "text": "A card object represents a standard playing card."
      },
      {
        "start": 37.0,
        "duration": 3.2,
        "text": "It has two attributes, a rank and a suit."
      },
      {
        "start": 40.2,
        "duration": 4.8,
        "text": "For example, this card has a rank queen and a suit, hearts."
      },
      {
        "start": 45.0,
        "duration": 8.1,
        "text": "Now, with your human brain, you'd probably say a queen of hearts is equal to any other queen of hearts."
      },
      {
        "start": 53.1,
        "duration": 4.6,
        "text": "But it kind of depends what you're using those cards for."
      },
      {
        "start": 57.7,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "If I'm playing a matching game, then it only matters if the ranks and suits are the same."
      },
      {
        "start": 62.7,
        "duration": 3.5,
        "text": "Even if those cards came from different decks."
      },
      {
        "start": 66.2,
        "duration": 5.2,
        "text": "But if I'm doing a magic trick, were you signed this particular card?"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.4,
        "duration": 5.2,
        "text": "You probably wouldn't be too impressed if I just produced a different queen of hearts."
      },
      {
        "start": 76.6,
        "duration": 4.6,
        "text": "It's only equal if it's the same exact card."
      },
      {
        "start": 81.2,
        "duration": 6.1,
        "text": "When we define a class, Python can't safely assume things about the type's attributes."
      },
      {
        "start": 87.3,
        "duration": 5.2,
        "text": "Since we can technically add or delete attributes after an object's created,"
      },
      {
        "start": 92.5,
        "duration": 4.2,
        "text": "that's why it defaults to comparing objects based on identity."
      },
      {
        "start": 96.6,
        "duration": 8.3,
        "text": "But Python gives us, as the programmer, the option to override that behavior, using the equals method."
      },
      {
        "start": 104.9,
        "duration": 4.6,
        "text": "The equals method is a special method that we can add to our class definitions."
      },
      {
        "start": 109.5,
        "duration": 4.7,
        "text": "It tells Python how to compare two objects of that type."
      },
      {
        "start": 114.2,
        "duration": 6.0,
        "text": "Python will automatically execute this equals method anytime we compare a card object,"
      },
      {
        "start": 120.3,
        "duration": 4.0,
        "text": "meaning when we use the equals equals operator."
      },
      {
        "start": 124.3,
        "duration": 3.5,
        "text": "Passing in that first object for the first parameter."
      },
      {
        "start": 127.8,
        "duration": 5.2,
        "text": "And the second object we're comparing for the second parameter."
      },
      {
        "start": 133.0,
        "duration": 1.6,
        "text": "Let's break this down."
      },
      {
        "start": 134.6,
        "duration": 5.0,
        "text": "Right now, when I compare these two cards, Python says they're not equal."
      },
      {
        "start": 139.6,
        "duration": 4.9,
        "text": "But the behavior I actually want is for Python to consider two cards equal"
      },
      {
        "start": 144.5,
        "duration": 3.2,
        "text": "if they have the same rank and the same suit."
      },
      {
        "start": 147.6,
        "duration": 4.2,
        "text": "So I can go to my card class definition and add the special method,"
      },
      {
        "start": 151.8,
        "duration": 4.8,
        "text": "underscore underscore EQ underscore underscore."
      },
      {
        "start": 156.6,
        "duration": 2.6,
        "text": "This is the name for the equals method."
